04712nam a22006855i 9780691206899DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191996nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912068997 a10.1515/97806912068992doi  a(DE-B1597)544955  a(OCoLC)1143802317  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aQL568.F7B63 1995 7aSCI0270002bisacsh04a595.79/60452481 aBourke, Andrew F.G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSocial Evolution in Ants /cNigel R. Franks, Andrew F.G. Bourke. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (550 p.) :b35 line illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMonographs in Behavior and Ecology ;v6200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. Kin Selection -- t2. Levels-of-selection Theory, Gene Selectionism, and Insect Societies -- t3. Kin Selection, Haplodiploidy, and the Evolution of Eusociality in Ants -- t4. Sex Ratio Theory for the Social Hymenoptera -- t5. Tests of Sex Ratio Theory in Ants -- t6. Kin Conflict over Sex Allocation -- t7. Kin Conflict over Reproduction -- t8. Evolution and Ecology of Multiple-queen Societies -- t9. Life History Theory in Ants -- t10. The Diversity of Life Histories in Ants -- t11. Mating Biology -- t12. The Division of Labor -- tReferences -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index -- tTaxonomic Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBiologists since Darwin have been intrigued and confounded by the complex issues involved in the evolution and ecology of the social behavior of insects. The self-sacrifice of sterile workers in ant colonies has been particularly difficult for evolutionary biologists to explain. In this important new book, Andrew Bourke and Nigel Franks not only present a detailed overview of the current state of scientific knowledge about social evolution in ants, but also show how studies on ants have contributed to an understanding of many fundamental topics in behavioral ecology and evolutionary biology. One of the substantial contributions of Social Evolution in Ants is its clear explanation of kin selection theory and sex ratio theory and their applications to social evolution in insects. Working to dispel lingering skepticism about the validity of kin selection and, more broadly, of "selfish gene" theory, Bourke and Franks show how these ideas underpin the evolution of both cooperation and conflict within ant societies. In addition, using simple algebra, they provide detailed explanations of key mathematical models. Finally, the authors discuss two relatively little-known topics in ant social biology: life history strategy and mating systems. This comprehensive, up-to-date, and well-referenced work will appeal to all researchers in social insect biology and to scholars and students in the fields of entomology, behavioral ecology, and evolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAntsxBehavior. 0aKin selection (Evolution). 0aSex ratio. 0aSocial evolution in animals. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh1 aFranks, Nigel R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691206899zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691206899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691206899.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA1